  <h2>The Mobile-First Filipino Market</h2>

  <p>The Philippines is one of the most mobile-centric gaming markets in the world. Over 80 percent of online gaming sessions in the country originate from smartphones, driven by the widespread adoption of affordable Android devices and the ubiquity of GCash and Maya as mobile payment platforms. Fixed broadband penetration remains low relative to peers like Thailand and Malaysia, making mobile optimization not just a preference but a necessity.</p>

  <p>Altenar's ArenaPlus deployment has been designed mobile-first, with the desktop experience treated as a secondary consideration. The interface is built as a progressive web app (PWA) that loads quickly on 4G connections, with a data-light design that minimizes bandwidth consumption. In-play betting features, which require real-time data streaming, have been optimized for intermittent connectivity.</p>

  <p>"In the Philippines, the sportsbook experience is fundamentally a mobile experience," Su said. "Our users are betting from jeepneys, from offices, from their homes in the provinces. If the app doesn't work seamlessly on a mid-range Android phone with a 4G connection, you've lost the market."</p>

  <h2>Sports Betting Within the PIGO Framework</h2>

  <p>Sports betting accounts for approximately 35 percent of total PIGO gross gaming revenue in the Philippines, a share that has been growing as domestic leagues resume full schedules and international sports calendars normalize. ArenaPlus, as the dominant PIGO sportsbook, captures a disproportionate share of this segment.</p>

  <p>The PIGO framework, established after the 2024 POGO ban, permits licensed operators to offer online sports betting, casino games, and other regulated gaming products to players physically located in the Philippines. Unlike the earlier e-Games framework, which was primarily casino-focused, PIGO explicitly encompasses sports betting and has attracted operators who specialize in the vertical.</p>

  <h2>Competitive Implications</h2>

  <p>The Altenar partnership gives ArenaPlus access to a technology stack that has been deployed in over 30 regulated markets globally, including Latin America, Africa, and Europe. This is a significant upgrade from the platform's previous in-house sportsbook technology, which lacked the depth of pre-match and in-play markets that international-grade platforms offer.</p>

  <p>For competitors, the move raises the bar. Other PIGO sportsbook operators, many of which use white-label solutions from smaller providers, will need to invest in their own technology upgrades to remain competitive. The introduction of PBA player props, in particular, creates a product differentiation that may be difficult to replicate quickly, given the proprietary data modeling required.</p>

